<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1666,2012]" lastBlockId="18.[151,1436,152,218]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1826,1852]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from all other congeners by the following combined morphological features: 
<number box="[151,224,1866,1892]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="27.0" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="25.0">25–29</number>
scales in longitudinal series (
<emphasis box="[584,616,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">vs.</emphasis>
<number box="[626,703,1866,1892]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="23.5" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="23.0">23–24</number>
), pectoral fins with vertical rows of small dark gray spots or dark gray bars in males (
<emphasis box="[460,491,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">vs.</emphasis>
pectoral fins without dark marks), frontal squamation F-patterned (
<emphasis box="[1317,1348,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">vs.</emphasis>
D-patterned), anterior section of supraorbital series of neuromasts continuous (
<emphasis box="[1055,1087,1947,1972]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">vs.</emphasis>
interrupted), dark marks on flanks mainly obliquely arranged in females (
<emphasis box="[686,718,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">vs.</emphasis>
mainly longitudinally or irregularly arranged), 
<number box="[1277,1292,1986,2012]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[1324,1335,1986,2012]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[1363,1436,1986,2012]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="19.0" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="17.0">17–21</number>
+ 
<number box="[177,192,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
infraorbital neuromasts (
<emphasis box="[495,526,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">vs.</emphasis>
<number box="[536,550,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[586,597,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[627,699,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="15.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="13.0">13–17</number>
+ 
<number box="[735,748,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
), caudal-fin rays 
<number box="[963,1036,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="26.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="26.0">26–27</number>
(
<emphasis box="[1055,1087,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">vs.</emphasis>
<number box="[1096,1173,152,178]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="29.5" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="28.0">28–31</number>
), and oblique rows of dark brown dots forming oblique bars on flanks in females (
<emphasis box="[855,887,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">vs.</emphasis>
never forming bars).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
